<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">The species can be recognized by a completely troglobiotic form with no eyes, an unpigmented body, and a roundly triangular syncoxital lobe.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Golovatch, SI" journalOrPublisher="Zoosystema" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" pagination="887 - 915" refId="B5" refString="Golovatch, SI, Geoffroy, JJ, Mauries, JP, 2006. Review of the millipede genus Hyleoglomeris Verhoeff, 1910 (Diplopoda, Glomerida, Glomeridae), with descriptions of new species from caves in Southeast Asia. Zoosystema 28 (4): 887 - 915" title="Review of the millipede genus Hyleoglomeris Verhoeff, 1910 (Diplopoda, Glomerida, Glomeridae), with descriptions of new species from caves in Southeast Asia." volume="28" year="2006">Golovatch et al. (2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.15298/arthsel.22.3.02" author="Golovatch, SI" journalOrPublisher="Arthropoda Selecta" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" pagination="201 - 206" refId="B6" refString="Golovatch, SI, Geoffroy, JJ, VandenSpiegel, D, 2013. On several new species of the millipede family Glomeridae from Vietnam (Diplopoda: Glomerida). Arthropoda Selecta 22 (3): 201 - 206, DOI: https://doi.org/10.15298/arthsel.22.3.02" title="On several new species of the millipede family Glomeridae from Vietnam (Diplopoda: Glomerida)." url="https://doi.org/10.15298/arthsel.22.3.02" volume="22" year="2013">2013</bibRefCitation>
), the new species seems to belong to the troglobiont species group containing 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. speophila" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="speophila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. speophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. spelaea" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="spelaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. spelaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. cavernicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="cavernicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. cavernicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. differens" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="differens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. differens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Golovatch, Geoffroy &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mauriès">Mauries</normalizedToken>
, 2006, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. reducta" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="reducta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. reducta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Golovatch, Geoffroy &amp; 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mauriès">Mauries</normalizedToken>
, 2006, and 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. albicorporis" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="albicorporis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. albicorporis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhang &amp; Zhang, 1995. These species are characterized by a totally unpigmented body. However, the new species differs from these species in lacking ocelli and the telopods bearing a roundly triangular syncoxital lobe. In contrast, the other species have convex ocelli, telopods with a roundly subtraperziform syncoxital lobe (
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. speophila" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="speophila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. speophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. cavernicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="cavernicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. cavernicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. reducta" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="reducta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. reducta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. albicorporis" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="albicorporis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. albicorporis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or a subquadrate syncoxital lobe (
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. spelaea" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="spelaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. spelaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or a roundly triangular syncoxital lobe (
<taxonomicName genus="H." lsidName="H. differens" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" rank="species" species="differens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">H. differens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
From the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi" authorityYear="2022" class="Diplopoda" family="Glomeridae" genus="Hyleoglomeris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyleoglomeris alba" order="Glomerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Hyleoglomeris alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, meaning white. It was used to emphasize the unpigmented body of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="161" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
Body length 4.38 mm, width of the second segment ~ 2.02 mm. Color entirely white, unpigmented (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. A, B Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., habitus C Ky Rang cave, dark zone. Images not to scale." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705328" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">6</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., holotype A left antenna B right antenna and Toemoesvary's organ C left hyposchism, dorsal view D pygidium, posterior view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705330" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">8</figureCitation>
). Ocelli totally absent. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="TÖmÖsvary’s">TOemOesvary's</normalizedToken>
organ transverse, strongly horseshoe-shaped, ~ 2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as wide as long (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., holotype A left antenna B right antenna and Toemoesvary's organ C left hyposchism, dorsal view D pygidium, posterior view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705330" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">8B</figureCitation>
). Antennae long and slender, antennomere, ~ 3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, antennal tip with four apical sensory cones (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., holotype A left antenna B right antenna and Toemoesvary's organ C left hyposchism, dorsal view D pygidium, posterior view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705330" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">8A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705328" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" start="Figure 6" startId="F6">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Figure 6.</emphasis>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">A, B</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi" authorityYear="2022" class="Diplopoda" family="Glomeridae" genus="Hyleoglomeris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyleoglomeris alba" order="Glomerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="161" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">Hyleoglomeris alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., habitus 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">C</emphasis>
Ky Rang cave, dark zone. Images not to scale.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="161">
Collum semicircular, with a trace of a transverse oval spot in the center and two distinctly transverse striae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., holotype A whole body, dorsal view B lateral view C ventral view D collum, anterior view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705329" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">7D</figureCitation>
). Second tergum with a narrow hyposchism, not reaching the caudal margin, with seven or eight striae, five or six of which cross the dorsum. Anal shield rounded, very slightly concave medio-caudally (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Hyleoglomeris alba Nguyen, Kuroda &amp; Eguchi, sp. nov., holotype A left antenna B right antenna and Toemoesvary's organ C left hyposchism, dorsal view D pygidium, posterior view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.85423.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/705330" pageId="0" pageNumber="161">8D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
